8.2.1 Flow Control
------------------

Decks, slides, and actions implement the ‚Äòdslide-stateful-sequence‚Äô
interface.  On each call to ‚Äòdslide-deck-forward‚Äô or
‚Äòdslide-deck-backward‚Äô, the deck receives the first call to its
‚Äòdslide-forward‚Äô method.  First, the deck will check for any step
callbacks.  (These may be added with ‚Äòdslide-push-step‚Äô in actions or
babel blocks.)  If there are no step callbacks, the deck delegates
‚Äòdslide-forward‚Äô to the slide.  The slide may delegate down to an
action, which may then further delegate to a child slide and so on.
Eventually, an action will implement the step.

   The return value tells the parent if progress was made.  In the most
basic case, each delegate will try all of its actions until one returns
non-nil.  The delegate returns the first non-nil result.  If the
delegate returns nil, it means it was unable to make progress, and so
the caller will instead try its own next action.  The deck will find a
root level sibling and hydrate it using ‚Äòdslide--make-slide‚Äô.  A child
action would find the next child and hydrate that.

   The moment of calling ‚Äòdslide-final‚Äô can vary depending on the
situation.  If there is only one slide at a time, ‚Äòdslide-final‚Äô is
usually called right after the child returns nil.  If the child is one
of several, such as with ‚Äòdslide-slide-action-inline‚Äô, then only after
all children complete will they have their ‚Äòdslide-final‚Äô called.  If
the presentation is quit early or the contents are opened,
‚Äòdslide-final‚Äô is also called, possibly before all steps are complete.

   Whenever all slides and actions return nil all the way back up to the
deck, it looks for a next or previous top-level heading to make into a
slide.  If none is found, it indicates that the user is at the beginning
or end of the presentation.

   The deck object and slide actions frequently create new children from
org headings.  They call their ‚Äòdslide-begin‚Äô or ‚Äòdslide-end‚Äô methods
right after that.  If these methods don‚Äôt indicate progress, the
‚Äòdslide-forward‚Äô or ‚Äòdslide-back‚Äô method will be called.


